00:41:40.440 --> 00:41:49.630
In Indonesia, there's some evidence that there's
a sort of clever young move back towards it.

00:41:49.630 --> 00:41:53.640
Islam is much more difficult to get any kind
of decent polling numbers, because people

00:41:53.640 --> 00:41:57.580
are extremely reluctant to say they don't
believe in God.

00:41:57.580 --> 00:42:01.000
And I should add, that's true of pretty much
all statistics dealing with religion.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:04.690
So I try to take it in broad brushes rather
than claiming particular bits.

00:42:04.690 --> 00:42:10.210
Q One last question was about corruption.
Do you have any observations on corruption

00:42:10.210 --> 00:42:11.210
and religion?

00:42:11.210 --> 00:42:16.619
John Micklethwait: Well, I suppose, yeah.
I do have one observation which has to do

00:42:16.619 --> 00:42:21.650
with foreign policies.
I think, I am personally always keen on religious,

00:42:21.650 --> 00:42:25.680
particularly religious parties, getting -- I'm
not saying I'm keen on saying religious parties

00:42:25.680 --> 00:42:29.590
getting into power, it could be misinterpreted
 -- but an advantage of religious parties

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:34.590
getting into party and I think a lesson for
the West is, if you have a party like the

00:42:34.590 --> 00:42:38.140
AK party, let them get into power.
They should have done the same in Algeria.

00:42:38.140 --> 00:42:42.781
Whenever you let a religious party come in
 -- and you could argue this is probably true

00:42:42.781 --> 00:42:49.600
also of things like with the Muslim Brotherhood
in Egypt -- it's true of arguably of Hamas

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:54.180
in Palestine.
If you let these people get power, they end

00:42:54.180 --> 00:42:58.800
up being more like other politicians than
they certainly ever intended to be.

00:42:58.800 --> 00:43:02.359
They have to cut deals.
They do -- things like corruption increase.

00:43:02.359 --> 00:43:07.390
To some extent, that special degree of moral
superiority, which religious parties can bring

00:43:07.390 --> 00:43:11.609
only when they're in opposition.
For the moment, Egypt would be a classic example.

00:43:11.609 --> 00:43:15.940
You have the deeply corrupt and not altogether
pleasant Barack regime.

00:43:15.940 --> 00:43:20.380
You have the Muslim Brotherhood, which has
some pretty weird ideas, but basically if

00:43:20.380 --> 00:43:25.890
you're going to meet them, they do evince
a type of honesty and straightforwardness

00:43:25.890 --> 00:43:32.400
which you don't always get from the regime.
______ The Egyptians won't in any way allow

00:43:32.400 --> 00:43:35.700
the Muslim Brotherhood to do anything.
The Americans are paranoid about it, because

00:43:35.700 --> 00:43:41.380
they sort of see senses a cousin of his brother
in Hamas actually letting them into power.

00:43:41.380 --> 00:43:45.369
I think the more power they have, the more
people will begin to see how realistic it

00:43:45.369 --> 00:43:48.270
is.
Ahmadinejad's another example of somebody

00:43:48.270 --> 00:43:55.430
who claimed to be a religious zealot, but
actually remains there, because he stuffed

00:43:55.430 --> 00:43:57.510
ballot boxes.

00:43:57.510 --> 00:44:03.520
Q There is talk that the _________ works of
which Dawkins and Sam Harris and everybody

00:44:03.520 --> 00:44:08.860
who think along those lines are actually doing
the cause of secularism damage, because it's

00:44:08.860 --> 00:44:10.900
drawing people towards religion.
I just wondered if you wanted to comment on

00:44:10.900 --> 00:44:11.900
that?

00:44:11.900 --> 00:44:16.790
John Micklethwait: I think Dawkins is interesting.
Any time I talk to Dawkins about it, he's

00:44:16.790 --> 00:44:24.860
obsessed by the big, scientific pictures.
But actually, he's -- the idea that the sort

00:44:24.860 --> 00:44:26.340
of facts.
I said to him, "Look, it's actually interesting.

00:44:26.340 --> 00:44:28.190
Religion seems to be doing very well despite
you.”

00:44:28.190 --> 00:44:32.020
[laughter] He didn't seem too obsessed by
that.

00:44:32.020 --> 00:44:37.700
I think Hitchens is probably more angry about
it than Sam Harris is.

00:44:37.700 --> 00:44:42.850
There is an element whereby what always tends
to happen is, once one side exaggerates its

00:44:42.850 --> 00:44:45.180
case.
Particularly American politics -- the recent

00:44:45.180 --> 00:44:49.369
history of American politics -- has been one
of overreach by one side followed by the other.

00:44:49.369 --> 00:44:56.480
You have the 60's, with a profound, liberal,
idiotic term for them, but you have a "leftish"

00:44:56.480 --> 00:45:01.160
overreach in the 60's followed by 30, 40 years
of conservatives.

00:45:01.160 --> 00:45:05.650
You could argue, with Bush, you then have
a pretty big overreach by the right.

00:45:05.650 --> 00:45:09.420
And then, it's now balancing again.
So I would expect something.

00:45:09.420 --> 00:45:24.070
Q I have a question about your positive evaluation
of phenomenon and justifying it because people

00:45:24.070 --> 00:45:29.810
obviously have more choice.
And I would just say the negative aspect of

00:45:29.810 --> 00:45:35.380
it is that, not only there's a choice in what
I spiritually choose to believe, but also

00:45:35.380 --> 00:45:42.740
it presents itself as it creeps into the daily
life by, for example, that creationism presents

00:45:42.740 --> 00:45:49.650
itself as a choice and alternative to evolution.
And I would argue thus that the tapestry of

00:45:49.650 --> 00:45:55.440
different religions that you have and you
can choose between them, somehow also leads

00:45:55.440 --> 00:46:04.570
us to believe that basically scientific facts
are being disregarded for the sake of pluralism.

00:46:04.570 --> 00:46:14.000
Hence I would still argue in favor of modernity
being understood as secularism in terms of

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:19.480
that religion simply is often challenged by
science and that scientific arguments are

00:46:19.480 --> 00:46:24.240
not being taken enough into account by religious
people.

00:46:24.240 --> 00:46:27.510
John Micklethwait: I think that's a choice
you have to make.

00:46:27.510 --> 00:46:31.330
For my book, pluralism is the greater good
out of those two.

00:46:31.330 --> 00:46:37.600
There will be some elements of creationism.
They tend to get pushed back.

00:46:37.600 --> 00:46:41.700
You could argue it's worse you say from some
perspectives.

00:46:41.700 --> 00:46:44.250
A, you've got the antiscientific lot.
You've also got, as I said earlier -- one

00:46:44.250 --> 00:46:50.600
interesting thing about the free market is,
it seems to encourage people with very strong

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:52.130
brands.
I mean, the Pentecostals are probably the

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:55.950
least scientific out of all the Christian
ones, and they're the ones who are doing best.

00:46:55.950 --> 00:47:02.910
So there is that risk.
That I'm either -- the one religion that I'm

00:47:02.910 --> 00:47:05.681
fundamentalist on the market, but I think
that you have to open up.

00:47:05.681 --> 00:47:07.661
But then, I think it's the fundamentally liberal
thing to do.

00:47:07.661 --> 00:47:12.410
You give people the chance to understand how
it works.

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:18.160
For me, there's no better thing to lose faith
in Creationism than to visit, I think it's

00:47:18.160 --> 00:47:22.720
the Creation Museum in Kentucky, where very
nice people try to explain to you -- and they're

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:26.359
extremely earnest, and some of them even have
rather strange doctrines.

00:47:26.359 --> 00:47:31.099
But try to explain to you how, because they
have cram the whole of human history into

00:47:31.099 --> 00:47:35.290
2000 years -- you literally go from Adam and
Eve.

00:47:35.290 --> 00:47:40.120
And so, like 53 years later, there's dinosaurs
running around really quickly, 'cause I know

00:47:40.120 --> 00:47:42.460
those existed.
And then, suddenly we're into Abraham.

00:47:42.460 --> 00:47:49.450
And it's patently wrong, and I think anyone
who goes to see it, gets that quite quickly.

00:47:49.450 --> 00:47:56.490
Just intellectually, I'm inherently -- I'm
on the, "I feel lucky" part of the thing.

00:47:56.490 --> 00:48:01.550
Sorry, Peter, yeah.

00:48:01.550 --> 00:48:04.930
Q [inaudible]

00:48:04.930 --> 00:48:15.730
John Micklethwait: Google as a religion is
interesting.

00:48:15.730 --> 00:48:21.340
I think technology is part of the -- what's
interesting about these people -- what's interesting

00:48:21.340 --> 00:48:25.900
about religious people is that, I mean, at
one point we thought about putting this, but

00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:29.480
it became difficult to maintain.
