you've kind of visited through your research
for the book, what was one experience that

00:49:49.099 --> 00:49:51.651
really affected you or kind of stayed with
you?

00:49:51.651 --> 00:49:58.349
John Micklethwait: There's two.
I think the exorcism in Brazil was fairly

00:49:58.349 --> 00:50:03.970
nonBrazilian -- was a fairly extraordinary
experience.

00:50:03.970 --> 00:50:11.020
You go to a sort of normal middleclass -- kind
of middle to working class -- suburb of Sao

00:50:11.020 --> 00:50:14.401
Paolo.
You sit there in one of those large churches

00:50:14.401 --> 00:50:18.310
that don't have much of an altar.
And then, you think you imagine you got the

00:50:18.310 --> 00:50:22.330
wrong time, because there's three exorcisms
a week and it's -- I think it was -- three

00:50:22.330 --> 00:50:26.740
o'clock on Wednesday.
I compounded the error by having -- we had

00:50:26.740 --> 00:50:33.150
a meeting of all the Latin American correspondents
of The Economist in Sao Paolo that day, and

00:50:33.150 --> 00:50:36.599
it ended at lunchtime.
And I foolishly said I was going off to an

00:50:36.599 --> 00:50:38.950
exorcism afterwards.
And that sort of, two of them and their girlfriends

00:50:38.950 --> 00:50:41.800
said they want to come too.
And you sort of arrive -- It's a bit like

00:50:41.800 --> 00:50:44.750
a sort of bad house party arrives in the middle
of this church and you're sitting there in

00:50:44.750 --> 00:50:48.840
this large place, and everyone's filing in.
And then, a huge number of housewives come

00:50:48.840 --> 00:50:53.130
in with their shopping, children -- you get
the general impression they just dropped off

00:50:53.130 --> 00:50:55.330
their laundry, they're picking up their children
from school.

00:50:55.330 --> 00:50:58.270
And again, everyone's just sort of sitting
around quite normally.

00:50:58.270 --> 00:51:05.609
And then, by within the next barely takes
an hour they're reduced to these quivering

00:51:05.609 --> 00:51:11.480
wrecks where you see the same woman who just
walked in beside you with her children is

00:51:11.480 --> 00:51:14.831
lying on the floor with people cursing spirits
out of them.

00:51:14.831 --> 00:51:19.190
It's a very strong thing -- exorcism -- in
Brazil, because a of people -- a lot of families

00:51:19.190 --> 00:51:26.960
who originally came from Africa to some extent
believe that when they left Africa, old tribal

00:51:26.960 --> 00:51:33.060
religions cursed them for the fact that they
were being stripped away as slaves to Brazil.

00:51:33.060 --> 00:51:38.180
And you see this thing where people are reduced
to this strange shape.

00:51:38.180 --> 00:51:42.380
And then what happened, almost the strange
thing were the children sit there play around

00:51:42.380 --> 00:51:47.220
in the back, watch their mothers descend to
the floor in this kind of profound emotional

00:51:47.220 --> 00:51:53.420
state, and then when the guy brings them back
out of it again, everyone picks up their shopping,

00:51:53.420 --> 00:51:59.599
the children all go running around to gather
around their mothers and walk out again.

00:51:59.599 --> 00:52:04.980
That extreme of emotion within an hour.
And the odd thing was talking to the pastor

00:52:04.980 --> 00:52:08.070
who did it.
Was sort of -- It's almost like talking to

00:52:08.070 --> 00:52:12.690
sort of like a surgeon after an operation.
Well, today was quite good.

00:52:12.690 --> 00:52:16.320
Five women I think we solved.
It was very kind of it's almost like he's

00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:21.070
sitting there making a cigarette.
That was profound.

00:52:21.070 --> 00:52:26.400
I also thought that on the less -- other side
of it -- you got a place like Nigeria.

00:52:26.400 --> 00:52:31.020
You actually see the religious war is most
intense.

00:52:31.020 --> 00:52:37.930
You see Christians, funded by American collection
plate money pushing northwards.

00:52:37.930 --> 00:52:42.300
And you see Islam funded by Saudi petrol dollars
coming southwards.

00:52:42.300 --> 00:52:46.680
And you just see this smashing together.
And you can go to a place then, a couple of

00:52:46.680 --> 00:52:50.560
weeks later, there's a fairly, large-size
massacre.

00:52:50.560 --> 00:52:53.960
So there's two.

00:52:53.960 --> 00:53:00.700
Q So you talked a lot about the rise of mainstream
religion, and I just wanted to see if you

00:53:00.700 --> 00:53:07.950
had any thoughts on the phenomenon behind
like, rising affiliation to sects.

00:53:07.950 --> 00:53:17.570
So like, maybe scientology, which has been
a huge uptake in the past few years, and I'm

00:53:17.570 --> 00:53:20.660
sure there are quite a few big ones?

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:26.270
John Micklethwait: Well, the truth is, some
of them are sects to the extent that they

00:53:26.270 --> 00:53:28.650
drag you in and they never really allow you
out.

00:53:28.650 --> 00:53:34.060
I didn't really go into Scientology in perhaps
the level it deserves, not least because they

00:53:34.060 --> 00:53:40.640
seem to be the most litigious group of religious
people in the history of the world.

00:53:40.640 --> 00:53:45.330
I think what you really -- I mean what de
Tocqueville said when he went to America was,

00:53:45.330 --> 00:53:49.820
he said the reason why America does so well
is multiplicity of sects.

00:53:49.820 --> 00:53:54.930
This is because what happened at the time
Methodism seems like a sect.

00:53:54.930 --> 00:54:00.109
It's the ability without trying desperately
to drag you back to your homeland.

00:54:00.109 --> 00:54:06.330
It's the Silicon Valley aspect of American
religion, which you see totally being mimicked

00:54:06.330 --> 00:54:11.770
in Asia, in Africa, and in Latin America,
actually, to a large extent, whereby people

00:54:11.770 --> 00:54:13.751
come and they set up.
And you can say a bit of East London's East

00:54:13.751 --> 00:54:18.340
End as well.
People come, people join one church, and then

00:54:18.340 --> 00:54:21.420
they don't really like this bit and so they'd
start a new one.

00:54:21.420 --> 00:54:26.000
And if you want a figure who, to me, sort
of symbolizes that form of modern religion

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:30.460
more than anyone else is Thomas Jefferson,
who -- Jefferson went through the Bible and

00:54:30.460 --> 00:54:37.119
cut out all the bits he did like and the bits
he didn't and threw out all the others away.

00:54:37.119 --> 00:54:40.790
And that was sort of his version of religion.
Well, I'll take this, this, this, this.

00:54:40.790 --> 00:54:47.700
And that tends to be how most new sects develop.
The established religions have generally done

00:54:47.700 --> 00:54:49.160
quite badly.
It's the newer ones which have kept pushing

00:54:49.160 --> 00:54:50.160
forward.

00:54:50.160 --> 00:54:51.210
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:54:51.210 --> 00:54:55.010
John Micklethwait: Thank you.

00:54:55.010 --> 00:54:55.950
&gt;&gt; [Clapping]

